<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">First major work day. The pieces become a plan.</p>
  <p>You have built the pieces: the area profile and baseline from Block 3, the allocation from Block 4, the quantified trade-off from Block 5. Today they become one document. You draft the <a href="/units/unit-6/assessment-sustainable-neighborhood-plan/">Sustainable Neighborhood Plan</a> end to end, and you add the part that turns analysis into a proposal: <strong>implementation recommendations</strong>, five or more concrete steps, each addressed to a real municipal body (the Greater Chennai Corporation, the CMDA, or your ward office).</p>
  <p>The thing that separates a strong recommendation from a weak one is specificity. "Protect green space" is not a recommendation, it is a wish. "Designate the strip along the old eri as protected wetland buffer, fund it through the corporation's stormwater budget, and phase it over two monsoons" is a recommendation, because it names what, who, when, and what it costs. The rubric rewards the second kind and caps the first. As you draft, keep the trade-off from Block 5 visible in the plan: the credible proposal is the one that says plainly what it gives up, not the one that pretends it gives up nothing.</p>
  <p>This is a protected work block. Mr. Ignash is conferencing the whole time, so bring the section that is fighting you. Both AI partners are open: the <a href="/ai-partners/urban-planner/">Urban Planner</a> for feasibility and form, the <a href="/ai-partners/equity-resilience-partner/">Equity &amp; Resilience Partner</a> for who pays. Every conversation that feeds the plan gets logged in your <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation</a>, including the one thing a partner got wrong.</p>
</section>

